  "prompt": "Why is the Mophie case charged by a micro-USB cable, and not a lightning cable?",
  "response": "The decision to use Micro-USB for charging Mophie cases rather than a Lightning cable is influenced by several factors:\n\n1. **Compatibility with Other Devices**: Micro-USB ports are widely used across various electronic devices, especially older or non-Apple devices. By using Micro-USB, Mophie can cater to a broader range of users who may already have Micro-USB cables and chargers on hand.\n\n2. **Cost and Manufacturing**: Micro-USB connectors tend to be cheaper to produce than Lightning connectors, allowing manufacturers to keep costs down and offer their products at competitive prices.\n\n3. **Universality and Standardization**: At the time many Mophie cases were designed, Micro-USB was the standard for many gadgets, making it a sensible choice for universal compatibility. Lightning cables are specific to Apple products, whereas Micro-USB is used in many other brands, adding to its universality.\n\n4. **Timing and Development**: Mophie might have opted for Micro-USB when they first developed their products in an era where Micro-USB was the prevalent standard. Transitioning to Lightning or other connectors might require redesign and additional costs.\n\nHowever, more recent products may use USB-C or Lightning connectors as technology and user needs evolve, reflecting updates in charging standards and consumer preferences.",
